        'content'     => 'Urgency words compress the decision timeline and discourage "I will come back later" behavior — which, statistically, means never. The core set includes "Limited Time," "Hurry," "Last Chance," "Ends Today," "Only X Left," "Act Now," "Before Midnight," and "Final Hours." Use urgency honestly: pair it with a real deadline or real inventory data. A countdown timer next to "Sale ends in 3h 42m" converts up to 9% better than a static banner. For product pages, "Only 4 left in stock" leverages scarcity while remaining truthful when tied to live inventory. Avoid stacking multiple urgency cues on the same page — it shifts from persuasive to desperate. The ideal placement is near the CTA button and in the email subject line. Example for a product page: "Hurry — Limited Time offer: get the Alpine Pro Jacket for 30% off. Ends today at midnight." Example for a category banner: "Last Chance: Winter Clearance — up to 60% off boots, coats, and accessories. Only 48 hours left." Example for a cart reminder email: "Your cart is waiting — but this price is not. These items sell out fast, and your discount expires tonight." Rotate urgency language seasonally so returning visitors do not develop banner blindness.',
