        'content'     => 'PAS works by making the reader feel the pain of their problem before offering relief. It is especially effective for products that solve a clear frustration. Problem: Name the specific pain point. "Your kitchen knives are dull. You are sawing through tomatoes instead of slicing them, and every meal prep takes twice as long as it should." Be precise — vague problems create vague interest. Agitation: Twist the knife (figuratively). Amplify the consequences of not solving the problem. "Dull knives are not just slow — they are dangerous. You apply more pressure, the blade slips, and suddenly you are reaching for a bandage instead of the cutting board. Plus, crushed ingredients mean uneven cooking, so even your recipes suffer." Agitation is not about fear-mongering; it is about helping the reader fully recognize a problem they have been tolerating. Solution: Present your product as the resolution with specificity. "The KitchenEdge Pro Chef Knife holds its edge for 6 months of daily use thanks to a Japanese VG-10 steel core at 61 HRC hardness. The ergonomic walnut handle reduces wrist fatigue, and the included honing rod keeps the blade sharp between professional sharpenings. Slice tomatoes paper-thin, dice onions in seconds, and actually enjoy cooking again." Example for skincare: Problem — "Waking up with dry, tight skin no matter how much moisturizer you apply." Agitation — "Layering products that do not absorb wastes money and clogs pores, making the problem worse." Solution — "Our Hydra Barrier Serum uses micro-encapsulated hyaluronic acid that penetrates three layers deep — one pump replaces your entire hydration step."',
