        'content'     => 'FAB bridges the gap between what a product is and why the customer should care. Most amateur product descriptions list features and stop. FAB forces you to translate every feature into a tangible benefit. Feature: A factual attribute of the product. "Made from 100% organic Pima cotton." This is objective and verifiable. Advantage: What that feature does better than the alternative. "Pima cotton fibers are 35% longer than standard cotton, which means the fabric pills less, holds its shape wash after wash, and feels noticeably softer against the skin." The advantage answers "So what?" Benefit: How the advantage improves the customer\'s life. "You get a t-shirt that still looks and feels brand-new after 50 washes — no more replacing basics every season. Your closet shrinks, your confidence grows, and your cost-per-wear drops to pennies." The benefit answers "Why should I care?" Apply FAB to every major selling point — most products have 3-5 features worth expanding. Example for a backpack: Feature — "40L capacity with a dedicated laptop compartment padded with EVA foam." Advantage — "Fits a 17-inch laptop securely while leaving room for a full day\'s gear, unlike single-compartment bags where your laptop slides against hard objects." Benefit — "Travel from office to gym to weekend trip with one bag — no more swapping packs or worrying about your laptop screen." Present the benefit first in bold or as a heading, then support it with the feature and advantage. Shoppers scan for benefits; they read features only after they are emotionally interested.',
