        'content'     => 'The Before/After formula sells the transformation rather than the product. It creates a vivid contrast between the customer\'s current frustrating reality and the improved life they will have after purchasing. Before: Describe the status quo with empathetic specificity. "Every morning is the same: you stand in front of the mirror trying to tame frizzy, uncooperative hair. The straightener takes 30 minutes, damages your ends, and the results barely last until lunchtime. By afternoon, humidity wins and you are back to a ponytail." The "Before" must resonate so deeply that the reader nods along. After: Paint the new reality with the product integrated naturally. "With the SilkSmooth Keratin Treatment, you wake up, run your fingers through sleek, manageable hair, and walk out the door. No heat tools. No 30-minute ritual. Just smooth, frizz-free hair that holds its shape for up to 72 hours — rain or shine. Your mornings get 25 minutes back, your hair stays healthier, and the ponytail becomes a choice, not a backup plan." The "After" must feel achievable, not fantastical. Ground it in real time savings, real frustrations removed, real activities enabled. Example for an office chair: Before — "By 2 PM your lower back aches, you are shifting every 10 minutes, and your productivity tanks." After — "The LumbarPro chair\'s adaptive support follows your posture throughout the day. You finish the workday without the familiar ache — and without noticing the chair at all, which is exactly how a great chair should work." Close with a CTA that references the transformation: "Make tomorrow morning different — shop now."',
