        'content'     => 'The Technical formula serves spec-driven buyers who research before purchasing — common in electronics, tools, fitness equipment, and automotive categories. Structure: Lead with the headline spec that differentiates the product, support with performance context, then compare against the relevant benchmark. Headline Spec: "4,800 mAh battery delivering 58 hours of playback on a single charge." Open with the number that matters most. For a drill, it is torque. For headphones, it is battery life. For a monitor, it is refresh rate. Performance Context: Translate the spec into a real-world scenario. "That is a full work week of 8-hour listening days before you even think about the charger. And with 10-minute fast charging giving you 5 hours of playback, even forgetting to charge is not a crisis." Performance context makes numbers relatable to non-experts while showing experts you understand real usage. Comparison: Benchmark against the category or the previous model. "The industry average for over-ear Bluetooth headphones is 30 hours. At 58 hours, the SonicPro X3 nearly doubles that — and outlasts the previous X2 model by 40%." Use a comparison table for multiple specs: Battery Life, Driver Size, Weight, Frequency Response, Active Noise Cancellation dB reduction, Codec Support. Example for a laptop: Headline — "M3 Pro chip with 18-core GPU." Performance — "Renders a 20-minute 4K timeline in Final Cut Pro in under 6 minutes." Comparison — "That is 2.5x faster than the Intel-based model it replaces, with half the fan noise." Close with a compatibility or ecosystem note: "Works with all Thunderbolt 4 accessories, backward-compatible with USB-C."',
